{"key":"post-12637172","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12637172</id>\n<content>One should never case after first flush.&amp;nbsp; It's normal for contaminant spores to land on a substrate during the course of a flush, where they sit harmlessly.&amp;nbsp; However, if you put a casing layer over these contaminant spores, you protect them and keep them nice and moist, allowing germination and the ruining of your project.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;All bulk substrates should be pasteurized.&amp;nbsp; If using anything but coir, it should be maintained at 140F to 160F for a full hour.&amp;nbsp; Don't ever pour boiling water on compost, manure or straw.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12637189</next>\n<prev>12637086</prev>\n<first>12636930</first>\n<last>12637212</last>\n<when>1274972476</when>\n<utime>05/27/10 06:01 PM</utime>\n</post>"}